## 5. Positioning advice & 60‑second pitch

If you have to pick one leading angle, lead with **“Etsy seller conversion + local coach”** and weave in “privacy and accessibility” as supporting differentiators.  

### Why not lead solely with “local/private”?

Local/offline is a fantastic differentiator for certain audiences, but by itself it sounds like a technical implementation choice, not an impact story; judges want impact expressed in human terms like “more income for small sellers” or “access to creative careers for blind people.” However, “local” becomes very compelling when you attach it to real stakes: sensitive wedding images, unreleased product designs, vulnerable artisans who can’t risk leaks, or rural sellers with unstable connectivity. [pixelpanda](https://pixelpanda.ai/blog/2026/03/16/etsy-product-photography-tips/)

### Why not lead solely with “accessibility”?

You could, but then you must show a real, working accessibility scenario, not a roadmap slide; assistive tech for blind creatives already exists, so judges will expect concrete UX and careful thought. Given 20 hours, you can probably build a thin but real vertical slice, but not an entire polished accessibility suite, so it’s better as a powerful supporting story. [cpr](https://www.cpr.org/2026/01/15/tactile-photography-accessible-art-for-the-blind/)

### Suggested 60‑second pitch

