## Strategic Recommendation for 20 Hours

Resist the urge to build. You have enough features. What you don't have is a sharp story.

**Hours 1–3: Cut and re-frame.**
Decide today: accessibility is the lead. Rewrite your README, submission summary, and pitch around one user persona. Studio and Quest modes are demoted to "the same engine also serves hobbyists and challenges."

**Hours 4–7: Get one real signal.**
Post in r/Blind, r/lowvision, an accessibility-focused Discord, or contact one disability organization. Ask for 15 minutes. Even a paragraph-long quote from someone who works in the space, with permission to use it, transforms your demo from speculative to grounded. If you can't get a real user, get a domain expert (an OT, an accessibility consultant, a vision rehabilitation specialist).

**Hours 8–12: Re-record the demo.**
Open with the persona story (don't show your face for the first 20 seconds — show the artisan's hands, or product photos getting better). Demo voice-first interaction. Show Gemma 4 E4B running locally, with the model name and inference time visible on screen — judges in the Gemma category need to *see* the Gemma usage, not be told. Three modes shown in a quick 30-second montage near the end, not as the structure.

**Hours 13–16: Polish the submission page.**
One hero image. Three crisp paragraphs. A link to a 60-second teaser cut of the demo for judges who don't watch the full thing. Make the technical credibility (schema-enforced JSON, CV grounding, multi-image compare, network isolation) visible as a sidebar so judges who care about engineering depth see it without it cluttering the story.

**Hours 17–19: Stress-test the demo.**
Run it on a laptop with WiFi off in front of a friend who hasn't seen it. If anything stalls, freezes, or surprises you, fix the surprise — don't add the next feature.

**Hour 20: Submit early.** Submission systems crash near deadlines.

What to explicitly NOT do: don't add features, don't add a fourth mode, don't try to integrate a new API, don't redo your tech stack, don't write a long blog post.

