## Suggested Video Narrative (3 minutes)

**0:00–0:20 — Open on the problem, not the product.**
A static or short clip: a pair of hands arranging a handmade item — a woven basket, a piece of jewelry, a small wooden carving. Voiceover (yours or synthesized) introduces the persona: name, place, craft, the fact that they're blind or low-vision and sell their work online. No product mentions yet. The viewer should feel the stakes before they see the tool.

**0:20–0:35 — Frame the gap.**
A line like: "She can make beautiful things. She can describe them. What she can't do is see whether the photo she just took will sell them." Hold on the gap for a beat.

**0:35–1:45 — Show the tool solving it, voice-first.**
Camera on the laptop screen. She takes/imports a photo. L.E.N.S. speaks: position of the object in the frame, lighting quality, background distraction, a specific suggestion. She acts on it. Take a second photo. Better. Show Gemma 4 E4B's name and the inference time briefly on screen — this is your Gemma category proof. Have one moment where you cut the WiFi visibly (airplane mode toggle) and the next critique still runs. This is your local-inference proof, shown not told.

**1:45–2:15 — Breadth montage.**
Quick cuts, 30 seconds total: Studio mode for a hobbyist, Quest mode for a student, Vault mode with a wedding photographer under NDA. No deep dives. Caption text only. The point is "the same engine serves many" — not "look at three products."

**2:15–2:45 — Why this matters and why Gemma.**
Three short claims, each on screen with brief voiceover: it runs entirely on-device with Gemma 4 E4B; it costs nothing after download; it works without internet, which is where many of the people who need it most actually live and work. End with the persona again — second photo side by side with the first.

**2:45–3:00 — Close.**
One sentence: what this is, who it's for, where to find it. URL on screen. Done. Don't pad.

A final note on this kind of demo: judges will watch many videos that open with the product. Almost none will open with the user. The cost of opening with the user is twenty seconds of attention. The benefit is being the one demo they remember in deliberation.

Good luck. Ship it.



