nd exposure issues before the image is published. This use case directly addresses the hackathon's "Digital Equity" track by democratizing access to professional marketing tools for low-resource micro-businesses.2. (D) Blind Artisans Photographing Handmade GoodsImpact Assessment: Extremely High (Social Good & Accessibility)Rationale: Visual impairment creates profound barriers to digital entrepreneurship and independent artistic expression. While applications like Microsoft's Seeing AI or Be My Eyes (utilizing GPT-4) provide general scene descriptions, they frequently lack the granular, localized spatial feedback necessary for an artist to independently set up a commercial product shot. By integrating voice accessibility with Gemma 4 E4B's vision encoder, L.E.N.S. could analyze the camera feed and verbally instruct the artisan (e.g., "The ceramic bowl is currently clipped on the left edge of the frame; tilt the camera slightly right"). This execution embodies the highest ideals of the "Digital Equity & Inclusivity" category, showcasing AI as a tool for profound individual autonomy.3. (E) Wedding/Commercial Photographers with NDA RequirementsImpact Assessment: High (Commercial Viability & Privacy Innovation)Rationale: This use case effectively weaponizes the "local/offline" architecture of L.E.N.S. as a definitive competitive moat. Commercial photographers shooting unreleased corporate products, proprietary intellectual property, or high-profile private events cannot legally utilize cloud-based critique tools like ChatGPT or Claude due to the risk of data ingestion. L.E.N.S.'s "Vault Mode" serves as a technologically elegant solution to a complex legal problem, proving that advanced multimodal analysis can coexist with absolute data sovereignty. This aligns perfectly with the hackathon's "Safety & Trust" track.4. (B) Hobbyist Photographers Getting FeedbackImpact Assessment: Moderate (Skill Building)Rationale: While technically sound, this application lacks the acute,